text: i'm a first-year student here at harvard
business school and prior to coming to
school here i founded and led a
not-for-profit organization called
strong women strong girls
when i graduated from college i started
that as my full-time job i was an
entrepreneur
and over the course of the next eight
years grew that to be a program serving
about three thousand girls a year
operating in five offices globally
so for me the hbs experience has been an
amazing opportunity to build my
confidence
and i think that that comes from in
large part the supportive community that
you create here
and i was a little nervous coming from
the non-profit sector that i wouldn't
fit in or that i wouldn't be kind of in
the right place for me
and what has turned out to be true is
two things the first is that my
classmates have been incredibly
supportive
from sitting with me to do tutoring
sessions about how to run the financial
models to really challenging me to think
about how to apply my non-profit skills
to the business community my classmates
have been amazing and then the second
thing that i've realized is that as
somebody coming from the social sector
my viewpoint and experiences are quite
unique and have a lot to contribute to
the classroom so rather than being
scared about that experience not being
enough of what it typically means to be
at hbs what i've come to realize is that
it's a real asset because it's given me
the ability to contribute
to 90 other people in my section and
help them to really think about how you
make a social impact as well
i have to say the thing that's been
really great about being here is that
that sense of let's take a problem and
figure out how to solve it and then
actually do something about it has been
pervasive so
in the classroom outside of the
classroom in social settings people are
just passionate and enthusiastic and
really focused on making this community
and the greater community a great place
to be
